  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">With 5 documents totaling 100K tokens, the multi-document result uses at most 30K tokens total across all documents</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">A small document (5K tokens) donates its unused budget from a 6K-per-doc allocation to the other four documents (leftover reallocation)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Parallel document retrieval is bounded at max 5 concurrent calls — SemaphoreSlim or equivalent present in the implementation</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">MergedChunks are ordered by relevance score (cross-document), not by document order</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Each document's chunks are preceded by `[Document: {filename}]` attribution header in the system prompt</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">No document text content appears in logs for any of the multiple documents (ADR-015)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet build` passes with no errors</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The `ChatHostContext.DocumentIds` field may need to be added if it only holds a single document ID
    currently. Check the model definition before implementing — if the field is already a collection,
    use it directly. If it is a single string, update the model and adjust callers accordingly (coordinate
    with the R2-013 task if file overlap exists, but DocumentContextService.cs and ChatHostContext.cs
    are different files so parallel execution should be safe).

    With very large document sets (20+ documents), the 30K/N allocation becomes extremely small per
    document. Consider adding a practical maximum of N=20 documents with a user-facing message if
    exceeded. This is defensive programming — the acceptance criteria only require 5 documents to work.
  </notes>

